{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18248"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18248"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10962"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10962"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18248"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7049"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27134"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe greater sciatic foramen is a part of the pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ligaments makes the primary contribution to its formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iliolumbar ligament","Inguinal ligament","Sacroiliac ligaments","Sacrospinous ligament","Sacrotuberous ligament"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe greater sciatic foramen is an important anatomical structure in the pelvis that allows the passage of several structures from the pelvis to the gluteal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esacrospinous ligament\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to the formation of the greater sciatic foramen. It extends from the sacrum to the ischial spine, and along with the sacrotuberous ligament, it forms the boundaries of the greater sciatic foramen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliolumbar ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament connects the ilium to the lumbar vertebrae and does not contribute to the sciatic foramina\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacroiliac ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E - These ligaments stabilise the sacroiliac joint but do not form the sciatic foramina\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacrotuberous ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - While it helps form the greater sciatic foramen, it is not the primary ligament responsible\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInguinal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament runs from the pubic tubercle to the anterior superior iliac spine and is not involved in the formation of the sciatic foramina\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sacrospinous ligament, along with the sacrotuberous ligament, forms the greater sciatic foramen.","The greater sciatic foramen is an important anatomical structure that allows passage of structures from the pelvis to the gluteal region.","The sacrospinous ligament extends from the sacrum to the ischial spine."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18248"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T21:20:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T21:20:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10962"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descript